heir striking ideas and beliefs, their convoluted mythologies and symbolism. Reviews of an earlier edition:“A book of prime importance for anyone interested in the history of religious dualism. The author’s knowledge of relevant original sources is remarkable; and he has distilled them into a convincing and very readable whole.”—Sir Steven Runciman“The most fascinating historical detective story since Steven Runciman’s Sicilian Vespers.”—Colin Wilson“A splendid account of the decline of the dualist tradition in the East . . . both strong and accessible. . . . The most readable account of Balkan heresy ever.”—Jeffrey B. Russell, Journal of Religion “Well-written, fact-filled, and fascinating . . . has in it the making of a classic.”—Harry T. Norris, Bulletin of SOAS  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristian heresiesxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030008253140uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300190144?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300190144423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300190144/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY